26","1250–Female":"1250–Zesnulá","1330":"1330","1284":"1284","1295":"1295","1250":"1250","1391":"1391","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1326":"1326","1259":"1259","1347":"1347","ca 1270":"okolo 1270","ca 1295":"okolo 1295","1339":"1339","Dussen, Noord-Brabant, Netherlands":"Dussen, Noord-Brabant, Nizozemsko","Dussen, Noord-Brabant, Nederland":"Dussen, Noord-Brabant, Nizozemsko","Nederland":"Nizozemsko"},"da":{"ca 1270–":"omkring 1270–Afdød","1270–Female":"1270–Afdød","1270–1330":"1270–1330","1284–1339":"1284–1339","1290–1347":"1290–1347","1295–1391":"1295–1391","1295–Female":"1295–Afdød","1259–1326":"1259–1326","1250–Female":"1250–Afdød","1330":"1330","1284":"1284","1295":"1295","1250":"1250","1391":"1391","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1326":"1326","1259":"1259","1347":"1347","ca 1270":"omkring 1270","ca 1295":"omkring 1295","1339":"1339","Dussen, Noord-Brabant, Netherlands":"Dussen, Noord-Brabant, Nederlandene","Dussen, Noord-Brabant, Nederland":"Dussen, Noord-Brabant, Nederlandene","Nederland":"Nederlandene"},"nl":{"ca 1270–":"circa 1270–Overleden","1270–Female":"1270–Overleden","1270–1330":"1270–1330","1284–1339":"1284–1339","1290–1347":"1290–1347","1295–1391":"1295–1391","1295–Female":"1295–Overleden","1259–1326":"1259–1326","1250–Female":"1250–Overleden","1330":"1330","1284":"1284","1295":"1295","1250":"1250","1391":"1391","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1326":"1326","1259":"1259","1347":"1347","ca 1270":"circa 1270","ca 1295":"circa 1295","1339":"1339","Dussen, Noord-Brabant, Netherlands":"Dussen, Noord-Brabant, Nederland","Dussen, Noord-Brabant, Nederland":"Dussen, Noord-Brabant, Nederland","Nederland":"Nederland"},"en":{"ca 1270–":"about 1270–Deceased","1270–Female":"1270–Deceased","1270–1330":"1270–1330","1284–1339":"1284–1339","1290–1347":"1290–1347","1295–1391":"1295–1391","1295–Female":"1295–Deceased","1259–1326":"1259–1326","1250–Female":"1250–Deceased","1330":"1330","1284":"1284","1295":"1295","1250":"1250","1391":"1391","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1326":"1326","1259":"1259","1347":"1347","ca 1270":"about 1270","ca 1295":"about 1295","1339":"1339","Dussen, Noord-Brabant, Netherlands":"Dussen, North Brabant, Netherlands","Dussen, Noord-Brabant, Nederland":"Dussen, North Brabant, Netherlands","Nederland":"Netherlands","nameMeanings":[{"name":"van","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Anh, Thanh, Hung, Minh, Vinh, Dung, Hue, Huong, Lan, Quang, Tan, Thuy, Hong, Chi, Hang, Ho, Pok, Sang, Bai, Chin, Ching, Chu, Chuan, Dong.","Vietnamese (<b>Vạn</b>): from the Chinese surname 萬, see   Wan   1.","Vietnamese (<b>Văn</b>): from the Chinese surnames 文 or 聞, see   Wen   2 and 3, and also 5 below."],"variants":[{"name":"Wan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Hong, Yi, Qi, Qiang, Wai, Yiu, Yuk, Chien-Min, Fang, Hin, Jichun, Li, Man, Chung, Min, Yiping, Pak, Sik, Sung Man.  Vietnamese Tin, Bang, Da, Hien, Hoi, Lan, Minh Quang, Sau, Tich, Tung, Yaping, Yuet.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 萬, which means ‘ten thousand’ literally or ‘very great number’ figuratively: (i) from the personal name of Bi Wan (畢萬), an official in the state of Jin (located in present-day Shanxi province). He was said to be a descendant of Bi Gong Gao (known as Duke of Bi), the 15th son of the virtuous King Wen of Zhou (reined 1152–1056  BC ). Bi Wan was later granted the fiefdom of Wei (魏), which in 403  BC  became the state of Wei (located in present-day Shanxi, Shaanxi, Henan and Hebei provinces). Some of his descendants adopted Wei (魏) as their surname, while others inherited 萬 (Wan), his personal name, as their surname. (ii) from the personal name Wan (萬), style name of Rui Bo (芮伯, the Earl of Rui), an official of the Western Zhou dynasty (1046–771  BC ), who was granted the fief Rui (located in Ruicheng in Shaanxi province). Some of his descendants inherited Rui (芮), the name of the fief, as their surname, while others inherited 萬 (Wan), his style name, as their surname. (iii) from the placename Wan (萬), the name of a fief (located in Juxian in Shandong province) granted during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ) to an official in the ancient state of Chu. (iv) from the first element of the name of the Wan Si (萬俟) family, who lived in the downstream areas of the Yellow River during the Northern Qi dynasty (550–577  AD ). (v) from the second element of the name of the Tu Wan (吐萬) family, who are members of the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 完, meaning ‘complete’ in Chinese: (i) said to be borne by the descendants of Huan Zhui, a grandson of the Duke Huan of Song (ruler of the state of Song, died 651  BC ). (ii) from Wan (完), the name of Qu Wan (屈完), an official in the state of Chu during the Spring and Autumn Period (770–476  BC ). (iii) shortened form of the compound surname Wan-Yan (完顔), a surname from minority ethnic groups such as Juchen ethnic group in ancient northern China."]}]},{"name":"Willem","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Jan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."]}]},{"name":"Willem","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Geertruijd Willem Jan Willem van Wijffliet was born about 1270, her father, Willem Jan Teylinc van Wijffliet, was 13 and her mother, echtgenote Willem Jan, was 22. She married Ridder Willem Arnoud Heyman van der Sluyse van Doveren. They were the parents of at least 4 daughters."},"et":{"ca 1270–":"umbes 1270–Surnud","1270–Female":"1270–Surnud","1270–1330":"1270–1330","1284–1339":"1284–1339","1290–1347":"1290–1347","1295–1391":"1295–1391","1295–Female":"1295–Surnud","1259–1326":"1259–1326","1250–Female":"1250–Surnud","1330":"1330","1284":"1284","1295":"1295","1250":"1250","1391":"1391","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1326":"1326","1259":"1259","1347":"1347","ca 1270":"umbes 1270","ca 1295":"umbes 1295","1339":"1339","Dussen, Noord-Brabant, Netherlands":"Dussen, Noord-Brabant, Madalmaad","Dussen, Noord-Brabant, Nederland":"Dussen, Noord-Brabant, Madalmaad","Nederland":"Madalmaad"},"fi":{"ca 1270–":"noin 1270–Kuollu